{"id":"quant-ph/0112084","submitter":"Boris Blinov","authors":"B.B. Blinov, L. Deslauriers, P. Lee, M.J. Madsen, R. Miller and C.\n  Monroe","title":"Sympathetic Cooling of Trapped Cd+ Isotopes","comments":"4 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 65, 040304(R) (2002)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.65.040304","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We sympathetically cool a trapped 112Cd+ ion by directly Doppler-cooling a\n114Cd+ ion in the same trap. This is the first demonstration of optically\naddressing a single trapped ion being sympathetically cooled by a different\nspecies ion. Notably, the experiment uses a single laser source, and does not\nrequire strong focusing. This paves the way toward reducing decoherence in an\nion trap quantum computer based on Cd+ isotopes.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Dec 2001 14:11:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0112085","submitter":"Alberto Rodriguez Gonzalez","authors":"J. D. Lejarreta and J. M. Cervero","title":"Intense laser interacting with a two level atom: WKB expressions for\n  dipole transitions and population inversion","comments":"11 pages, LaTex2e, no figures. To appear in Physics Letters A","journal-ref":"Physics Letters 293A, 1-9 (2002)","doi":"10.1016/S0375-9601(01)00844-1","report-no":"USAL-FT-02","categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In a previous paper, we have already considered the system composed by a two\nlevel atom interacting with a coherent external electromagnetic field. No\napplication whatsoever has been made of the rotating wave approximation. Being\nspecially interested in the problem of higher harmonic generations for the case\nof very intense laser fields, we have developed in this letter a much more\nefficient way to obtain these solutions as well as to carry out some\ncalculations in a range in which the parameters take extreme values. Also the\nformalism allows us now to provide analytic expressions in the WKB regime for\nthe electric dipole moment and the population inversion. The spectrum can be\ndecomposed in periodic and non-periodic contributions. Only the latter depends\nupon the Floquet exponent and can be responsible of the main complexities of\nthe observed Rabi revivals and the hyper-Raman shift.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 14 Dec 2001 15:20:50 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
